Entry type: Bug Fix
Task Worked on: dfs() base cases
Issue or decision: My first attempt had maze[r][c]==1 and it didn't check if r and c were in bounds. When it ran through
an online compiler it crashed.
Symptom: DFS tried to move off the edge of the maze grid
What I tried: Added cout<<r<<" "<<c<<endl; at the top to trace values. r ad c were going negative or going above
N/M before the wall check ran. This meant that maze[r][c]==1 was accessed out of range.
Fix: Reordered checks so out of bound comes first then the wall and then visited.
Commit: Fixed crash by checking bounds. (Fixed before commited to git hub)

Entry 3
Date: 2026-05-06
Entry Type: Bug fix
Task Worked On: Corrected parent tracking for path reconstruction
Issue: When DFS returned true, printPath() was printing (-1,-1) or looping indefinitely
Error Message: Output of (-1,-1) or the program froze after printing "Path from entrance to exit:" and never finished
Symptom: Program froze
What I tried: Read printPath() and saw it goes backwards through parent_r as well as parent_c until it gets to the entrance.
If the arrays contain -1 the while loop would never hit the entrance and it would run forever.
Fix: Moved the assignment to before the recursive call. I originally made the parent after the recursive call.
Commit: Encountered an error while testing and moved the parent assignment to run before the recursive call.

